{"title_page": "Donald J. Albanese", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Donald J. Albanese\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|state_assembly=New Jersey\n|district=[[15th Legislative District (New Jersey)|15th]]\n|term_start   = January 13, 1976\n|term_end     = January 12, 1982\n|predecessor  = [[Robert C. Shelton Jr.]]\n|successor    = [[Gerard S. Naples]]<br>[[John S. Watson (New Jersey politician)|John S. Watson]]\n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1937|6|26}}\n|birth_place  = [[Belvidere, New Jersey]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse={{marriage |Rosemarie Falcone |1970 |March 31, 2017 |end=d.}}\n}}\n\n'''Donald J. Albanese''' (born June 26, 1937) is an American [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] politician who served in the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] from 1976 to 1982.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Belvidere, New Jersey|Belvidere]], he attended public schools there and later graduated from [[Rider College]] in 1960. He also attended classes at [[George Washington University]], [[Lehigh University]] Graduate School of Business, and [[New York Institute of Finance]]. Albanese served in the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]] from 1955 to 1957. A [[certified public accountant]] by trade, Albanese lived in [[Lopatcong Township, New Jersey|Lopatcong Township]] near [[Phillipsburg, New Jersey|Phillipsburg]] where he maintained an accountants office.<ref name=LegManual>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oWgkAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Donald+J.+Albanese%22+belvidere ''Fitzgerald's Legislative Manual, 1979''], p. 232. Accessed October 15, 2018. \"Donald J. Albanese. Rep. Phillipsburg - Assemblyman Albanese was born in Belvidere June 26, 1937.\"</ref> Albanese later moved to [[Bangor, Pennsylvania]]. He was married to the former Rosemarie Falcone, a businesswoman who also served on various women's Republican committees, a vice-chair of the [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren County]] Republican Committee, and was an unsuccessful [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for the General Assembly in the [[23rd Legislative District (New Jersey)|23rd District]] in 1991.<ref name=1986_RA>{{cite news |url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1986-02-06-2513531-story.html |newspaper=[[The Morning Call]] |title=Warren GOP vice chairwoman announces bid for Freeholder |date=February 6, 1986 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=1991_RA>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/254745497/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |title=Dorsey spreads campaign wealth to GOP hopefuls |first=Colleen |last=O'Dea |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Morristown)|Daily Record]] |date=October 20, 1991 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> She died in 2017.<ref name=RosemarieObit>{{cite news |url=https://obits.lehighvalleylive.com/obituaries/etpa/obituary.aspx?n=rosemarie-a-albanese&pid=184826731&fhid=28239 |website=[[The Express-Times]] |date=April 4, 2017 |title=Rosemarie A. Albanese |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nFrom 1963 to 1969, he served as the president of the Belvidere Board of Education. He also served as the chair of the Belvidere Republican Committee in 1968 and the Lopatcong Township Republican Committee in 1974.<ref name=LegManual/> He first ran for the General Assembly in 1967 in the new [[15th Legislative District (New Jersey)|15th Legislative District]] stretching through [[Hunterdon County, New Jersey|Hunterdon]], [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren]], and [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]] counties. However, he was defeated for one of two seats in the Republican primary.<ref name=1967PrimaryElection>{{cite web |url=https://nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/election-results/1920-1970//1967-primary-election.pdf |title=Results of the Primary Election Held on September 12, 1967 |publisher=[[Secretary of State of New Jersey]] |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> In 1975, Albanese made a second attempt for the Assembly in the Republican Primary in the 15th District (this time encompassing Warren and Sussex counties and northern [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic County]]). He was again defeated (coming in third place) but one of two winners, Clifton E. Lawrence, died between the primary and general election.<ref name=1975PrimaryElection>{{cite web |url=https://nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/election-results/1920-1970//1975-primary-election.pdf |title=Results of the Primary Election Held on June 3, 1975 |publisher=Secretary of State of New Jersey |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Lawrence>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/08/archives/clifton-e-lawrence.html |title=Clifton E. Lawrence |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 8, 1975 |author=[[Associated Press|AP]] |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Albanese was ultimately placed on the Republican ticket and won the election alongside incumbent [[Robert E. Littell|Robert Littell]]. He was subsequently reelected in 1977 and 1979.\n\nWhile in the legislature, he served on the Assembly taxation committee and was vice chairman on the Joint Legislative Ethics Committee. Albanese compiled a conservative voting record voting against implementing the state income tax and public financing of gubernatorial elections. He was an early supporter of [[Ronald Reagan]]'s presidential bid and earned a 100-percent rating from the [[American Conservative Union]] (ACU).<ref name=CourierNews>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/220085499/ |title=Can't lose, boasts Albanese |first=Janet |last=Thompson |newspaper=[[The Courier-News]] |date=October 8, 1980 |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was also member of the ACU and the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=LegManual/> In 1980, he was a delegate to the [[1980 Republican National Convention|Republican National Convention]] and was later appointed by Reagan following his election to the presidency to the National Steering Committee on Business and the Citizens for America Committee.<ref name=LVL_2010>{{cite news |url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/elections/2010/01/donald_albanese_former_nj_asse.html |title=Donald Albanese, former N.J. assemblyman, considering run for Rich Grucela's seat |date=January 9, 2010 |newspaper=The Express-Times |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe first considered a run for [[Governor of New Jersey]] in [[1981 New Jersey gubernatorial election|1981]].<ref name=CourierNews/> Later, he dropped out of the Republican gubernatorial primary and instead challenged incumbent [[New Jersey Senate|State Senator]] [[Wayne Dumont]] in the Republican primary in the redistricted [[24th Legislative District (New Jersey)|24th District]].<ref name=1981_APP>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/145921698/ |title=GOP query - Who's the strongest? |first=Paul |last=Wolcott |newspaper=[[Asbury Park Press]] |date=May 26, 1981 |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Dumont defeated Albanese 60%\u201340%.<ref name=1981PrimaryElection>{{cite web |url=https://nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/election-results/1981/1981-primary-results-st-senate-gen-assembly.pdf |title=Candidates for the Offices of State Senate and General Assembly |publisher=Secretary of State of New Jersey |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Following his move to Pennsylvania, he ran for the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] in [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 137|District 137]]'s 2010 Republican primary. Albanese was defeated by eventual general election winner [[Joe Emrick]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/nazareth/2010/05/upper_nazareth_supervisor_jose.html |title=Upper Nazareth Supervisor Joseph Emrick captures GOP nod in 137th District House race |newspaper=The Express-Times |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albanese, Donald J.}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Jersey General Assembly]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Republicans]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Belvidere, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Lopatcong Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Northampton County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Warren County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rider University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lehigh University alumni]]\n[[Category:George Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:People of the Office of Naval Intelligence]]\n[[Category:American accountants]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Donald J. Albanese\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|state_assembly=New Jersey\n|district=[[15th Legislative District (New Jersey)|15th]]\n|term_start   = January 13, 1976\n|term_end     = January 12, 1982\n|predecessor  = [[Robert C. Shelton Jr.]]\n|successor    = [[Gerard S. Naples]]<br>[[John S. Watson (New Jersey politician)|John S. Watson]]\n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1937|6|26}}\n|birth_place  = [[Belvidere, New Jersey]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse={{marriage |Rosemarie Falcone |1970 |March 31, 2017 |end=d.}}\n}}\n\n'''Donald J. Albanese''' (born June 26, 1937) is an American [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] politician who served in the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] from 1976 to 1982.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Belvidere, New Jersey|Belvidere]], he attended public schools there and later graduated from [[Rider College]] in 1960. He also attended classes at [[George Washington University]], [[Lehigh University]] Graduate School of Business, and [[New York Institute of Finance]]. Albanese served in the [[Office of Naval Intelligence]] from 1955 to 1957. A [[certified public accountant]] by trade, Albanese lived in [[Lopatcong Township, New Jersey|Lopatcong Township]] near [[Phillipsburg, New Jersey|Phillipsburg]] where he maintained an accountants office.<ref name=LegManual>[https://books.google.com/books?id=oWgkAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Donald+J.+Albanese%22+belvidere ''Fitzgerald's Legislative Manual, 1979''], p. 232. Accessed October 15, 2018. \"Donald J. Albanese. Rep. Phillipsburg - Assemblyman Albanese was born in Belvidere June 26, 1937.\"</ref> Albanese later moved to [[Bangor, Pennsylvania]]. He was married to the former Rosemarie Falcone, a businesswoman who also served on various women's Republican committees, a vice-chair of the [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren County]] Republican Committee, and was an unsuccessful [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for the General Assembly in the [[23rd Legislative District (New Jersey)|23rd District]] in 1991.<ref name=1986_RA>{{cite news |url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1986-02-06-2513531-story.html |newspaper=[[The Morning Call]] |title=Warren GOP vice chairwoman announces bid for Freeholder |date=February 6, 1986 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=1991_RA>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/254745497/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |title=Dorsey spreads campaign wealth to GOP hopefuls |first=Colleen |last=O'Dea |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Morristown)|Daily Record]] |date=October 20, 1991 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> She died in 2017.<ref name=RosemarieObit>{{cite news |url=https://obits.lehighvalleylive.com/obituaries/etpa/obituary.aspx?n=rosemarie-a-albanese&pid=184826731&fhid=28239 |website=[[The Express-Times]] |date=April 4, 2017 |title=Rosemarie A. Albanese |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nFrom 1963 to 1969, he served as the president of the Belvidere Board of Education. He also served as the chair of the Belvidere Republican Committee in 1968 and the Lopatcong Township Republican Committee in 1974.<ref name=LegManual/> He first ran for the General Assembly in 1967 in the new [[15th Legislative District (New Jersey)|15th Legislative District]] stretching through [[Hunterdon County, New Jersey|Hunterdon]], [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren]], and [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex]] counties. However, he was defeated for one of two seats in the Republican primary.<ref name=1967PrimaryElection>{{cite web |url=https://nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/election-results/1920-1970//1967-primary-election.pdf |title=Results of the Primary Election Held on September 12, 1967 |publisher=[[Secretary of State of New Jersey]] |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> In 1975, Albanese made a second attempt for the Assembly in the Republican Primary in the 15th District (this time encompassing Warren and Sussex counties and northern [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic County]]). He was again defeated (coming in third place) but one of two winners, Clifton E. Lawrence, died between the primary and general election.<ref name=1975PrimaryElection>{{cite web |url=https://nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/election-results/1920-1970//1975-primary-election.pdf |title=Results of the Primary Election Held on June 3, 1975 |publisher=Secretary of State of New Jersey |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Lawrence>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/08/archives/clifton-e-lawrence.html |title=Clifton E. Lawrence |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 8, 1975 |author=[[Associated Press|AP]]|date=April 2020}} |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Albanese was ultimately placed on the Republican ticket and won the election alongside incumbent [[Robert E. Littell|Robert Littell]]. He was subsequently reelected in 1977 and 1979.\n\nWhile in the legislature, he served on the Assembly taxation committee and was vice chairman on the Joint Legislative Ethics Committee. Albanese compiled a conservative voting record voting against implementing the state income tax and public financing of gubernatorial elections. He was an early supporter of [[Ronald Reagan]]'s presidential bid and earned a 100-percent rating from the [[American Conservative Union]] (ACU).<ref name=CourierNews>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/220085499/ |title=Can't lose, boasts Albanese |first=Janet |last=Thompson |newspaper=[[The Courier-News]] |date=October 8, 1980 |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was also member of the ACU and the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=LegManual/> In 1980, he was a delegate to the [[1980 Republican National Convention|Republican National Convention]] and was later appointed by Reagan following his election to the presidency to the National Steering Committee on Business and the Citizens for America Committee.<ref name=LVL_2010>{{cite news |url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/elections/2010/01/donald_albanese_former_nj_asse.html |title=Donald Albanese, former N.J. assemblyman, considering run for Rich Grucela's seat |date=January 9, 2010 |newspaper=The Express-Times |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe first considered a run for [[Governor of New Jersey]] in [[1981 New Jersey gubernatorial election|1981]].<ref name=CourierNews/> Later, he dropped out of the Republican gubernatorial primary and instead challenged incumbent [[New Jersey Senate|State Senator]] [[Wayne Dumont]] in the Republican primary in the redistricted [[24th Legislative District (New Jersey)|24th District]].<ref name=1981_APP>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/145921698/ |title=GOP query - Who's the strongest? |first=Paul |last=Wolcott |newspaper=[[Asbury Park Press]] |date=May 26, 1981 |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Dumont defeated Albanese 60%\u201340%.<ref name=1981PrimaryElection>{{cite web |url=https://nj.gov/state/elections/assets/pdf/election-results/1981/1981-primary-results-st-senate-gen-assembly.pdf |title=Candidates for the Offices of State Senate and General Assembly |publisher=Secretary of State of New Jersey |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Following his move to Pennsylvania, he ran for the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] in [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 137|District 137]]'s 2010 Republican primary. Albanese was defeated by eventual general election winner [[Joe Emrick]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/nazareth/2010/05/upper_nazareth_supervisor_jose.html |title=Upper Nazareth Supervisor Joseph Emrick captures GOP nod in 137th District House race |newspaper=The Express-Times |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albanese, Donald J.}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Jersey General Assembly]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Republicans]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Belvidere, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Lopatcong Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Northampton County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Warren County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rider University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lehigh University alumni]]\n[[Category:George Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:People of the Office of Naval Intelligence]]\n[[Category:American accountants]]\n", "name_user": "Mr. Matt\u00e9", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_J._Albanese"}
